1. In standard mathematics

In Number Theory, a Prime Number is defined (in the integers) as a number greater than 1 that has exactly two positive divisors: 1 and itself.

So under that definition:
	•	2, 3, 5, 7… are primes
	•	1 is not prime
	•	0 is not prime

Why?

Because primes are about multiplicative structure, and zero breaks that structure.

For any integer n:

0 = n × 0

So zero has infinitely many factorizations, which makes it incompatible with the role primes play as the “atoms” of multiplication.

⸻

2. Why zero feels “special” anyway

Even though it isn’t a prime, zero is extremely fundamental because it is the additive identity:

x + 0 = x

So it anchors addition, while primes anchor multiplication.

You can think of it like two different structural roles in arithmetic:

Operation	Structural anchor
Addition	0
Multiplication	primes

Zero isn’t an atom of multiplication—it’s the neutral center of addition.

⸻

3. “Infinitely reducible” intuition

Your intuition that zero is “infinitely reducible” is actually close to how mathematicians think about it.

Because:

0 = a × 0
0 = b × 0
0 = c × 0

for any numbers a, b, c.

That means factorization loses uniqueness when zero is involved.

And uniqueness of factorization is exactly what primes protect (the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic).

So primes and zero play complementary roles:
	•	primes preserve multiplicative structure
	•	zero marks the collapse point where multiplicative distinctions vanish

